Calcareous ring of five radial and five interradials plates, lacking posterior processes (
Figure 2A, V
). Plates vary in robustness depending on their position in the calcareous ring, but are similar in shape between dorsal and ventral plates. Two radial and three interradial dorsal plates, taller and wider than their complementary ventral plates that are low and outstretched. Radial plates slightly wider in middle region than towards ends, at anterior and posterior margins with a center short slit pointing towards the center of the piece and this generates two short divisions in each of the margins. Interradial dorsal plates semi-square, at anterior parts gently curved and posterior margins with a marked slit pointing towards the center of the piece; in ventral region elongated and at posterior margins lightly concave.

Ecology . Environmental data available in the original description of
S. virgulasolida
included (one sample only): 1300 m depth, 5 °C, 0.20 ml O2/l, and sediments made of fine black mud ( Massin & Hendrickx, 2010 ). The specimens reported herein were collected in a much wider bathymetric range ( 710‒1102 m ), in 4.17‒5.81 °C, 0.15‒0.48 ml O2/l, and in 34.40‒34.48 ups. The species occurs in a wide variety of sediments made of 3.65‒12.08 % clays, 40.93‒84.46 % silt, and 5.34‒55.43 % sands, with an organic carbon content of 17.93‒52.02 mg /g (1.79‒5.20 % of organic matter) ( Table 1 ). Mexican records correspond to a bathymetric fringe located below the Oxygen Minimum Zone (OMZ) where a diverse community composed of mollusks, crustaceans, and other groups of echinoderms is known to occur (see Hendrickx et al ., 2011, 2016; Hendrickx & Serrano, 2010 ;
Papiol et al ., 2016
). Dissolved oxygen values measured close to the seafloor indicate that
S. virgulasolida
is able to tolerate mild (<0.5 ml O2/l) to severe (<0.2 ml O2/l) hypoxic conditions. The bathymetric range where it occurs is also favorable to species well adapted to oxygen deficiency due to reduced competition for food which, in the case of many sea cucumbers, consists mostly of organic particles (deposit or suspension feeding) ( Graham & Thompson, 2009 ). OMZ areas are known to be rich in organic deposits (
Papiol et al ., 2016
).
